		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV><BR>So sword and board is a downward scaling tool (or will be when we get Shieldmate weapons) because it actually gets better in lesser content where I'm not cutting down my DPS by using Defensive.<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Holy bejeebus... Shield Block is not downward scaling!&nbsp; Get it through your thick skull... the amount of damage avoided with Shields is not GREATER as the content becomes weaker.&nbsp; You don't block MORE damage when the mob hits for LESS.&nbsp; That's the definition of downward scaling.... if you don't know what it means, arguing on this thread about it is pointless.</P>
<P>In weaker content, I use a 2-hander, I lose all the benefits of an upward scaling&nbsp;Shield to gain all the benefits of&nbsp;greater DPS... why?&nbsp; Because if the content is no longer challenging, I'm never worried about my survival rate as much as the group is concerned with their killing rate.&nbsp; If I do use my Shield, it's because my 1-hander is currently setup for better aggro, and I lose out on a large chunk of DPS.</P>
<P>Your DPS is ALREADY a downward scaling ability, because when mobs have less hitpoints and are hit more often, you're doing more damage and a greater percentage of damage to the mob.&nbsp; Augmenting your ability to use an upward scaling tool to further increase your downward scaling DPS is going to effect the gap at higher ends, where an upward scaling ability is going to have the most benefit.</P>
<P>Thought for the day:&nbsp; Who would benefit more from Warriors gaining Shieldmates, the lower end Warrior looking to slum it with competing Knights in weaker content, or the raiding Warrior facing much more powerful mobs?</P>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
