<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=15294#M15294">398</a> of 481
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 131 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><div></div>Frod,<br><blockquote><i>"if it's not desirable to continue upgrades which trivialize everything"</i><br></blockquote>I'm glad you're not saying that's the case, b/c it's certainly not currently the case that the sum total of knight abilities vs group content trivialize everything.&nbsp; And if content is not being trivialized, there's no reason to even mention the word nerf.&nbsp; Focus on getting your own issues taken care of, not on other classes.&nbsp; Threatening "nerfs" if you don't get your way isn't cool (which is effectively what you've done here).&nbsp; Also, it's flat out overestimating your influence- if you haven't managed to get warrior tanking issues fixed, what makes you think you have the influence to nerf knights?&nbsp; The end result is just a lot of bickering on forums with no impact on the game (I think the thing people are getting away from here is EQ design is not done by comittee on public forums, it's done by professional game designers.&nbsp; And while they may sometimes incorporate suggestions from the playerbase, ultimately, the players- even class correspondents- don't make game design decisions).<br><blockquote><i>"When grouped with a warrior, if EQ is to be truly balanced... you,
having more roles than the warrior should not be tanking, and the
warrior should be.&nbsp; "<br></i></blockquote>When I'm grouped with a warrior from my guild... the warrior generally does tank.&nbsp; So I guess EQ isn't all that unbalanced after all.&nbsp; For EQ to be "truly balanced", all classes should be of roughly equal desirability in groups and in raids.&nbsp; For the game to be "truly balanced", the gap between a knight and a warrior in groups should <u><i><b>never</b></i></u> favor warrior tanks to the exclusion of knights.&nbsp; I.E., The situation should never be <i>"We need a tank.... grab a warrior!&nbsp; Oh... wait, haven't seen a warrior lfg for the last 15 minutes, I guess we can take that SK over there lfg....".</i>&nbsp; The situation should never be, when an SK is in a group, <i>"Ok, we're all set.... just need a tank!"</i> (to head into challenging content).&nbsp; Both of those scenarios have played out more than once in EQ's history.<br><br>My point is- any adjustments to warrior tanking power must be measured carefully to prevent history from repeating itself, and prevent the gap from becoming excessive.<br><br><hr size="2" width="100%"><br><br>Togam,<br><blockquote><i>"why&nbsp; be feigned ?&nbsp; i thought&nbsp; sk's&nbsp; were&nbsp; only tanks . pet&nbsp; dies ,&nbsp; you have auto aggro . auto&nbsp; aggro&nbsp; = good tank ."<br></i></blockquote>Depends on the exact circumstances, but not being feigned can sometimes get you aggro on more than just the mob you're trying to pull.&nbsp; To be safe, you might as well just feign.&nbsp; And yes, buffing a pet helps the survivability of the pet, but when group content is hitting for 1500.... a 2-3,000 base hp pet isn't going to survive for long (I'm not sure exactly how much hp our level 64 pet has, but that's what we usually use for pet pulling, as it ensures it's green to the mob being pulled- it's a level 41 warrior essentially).<br><blockquote><i>"you only&nbsp; gain&nbsp; less because&nbsp; you&nbsp; swing&nbsp; less . and cast&nbsp; more .&nbsp; you&nbsp;
only&nbsp; lose more if you&nbsp; swing&nbsp; less and cast&nbsp; more . stop&nbsp; the excess
casting&nbsp; and&nbsp; your aggro&nbsp; will&nbsp; be similar&nbsp; to&nbsp; warriors"<br></i></blockquote>No, my total melee aggro (melee damage + procs) will NOT be the same as a warriors if I'm not casting.&nbsp; Look up anger and static blow on lucy, please.&nbsp; Look at the differences in melee capabilities between a knight and a warrior as well.&nbsp; <br><br>And I do lose more and gain less than a warrior with respect to the potime stun proc clicky.&nbsp; Here, since you obviously don't get it, let me spell it out to you:&nbsp; You can only use one proc buff at a time.&nbsp; SK's have several proc buff lines already, all of which have DD components.&nbsp; DD aggro is one point of aggro per point of damage done.&nbsp; Best we do with our proc buffs is 402 damage, or 402 hate per proc.&nbsp; Replacing a 402 DD proc with the stun clicky from potime would gain us 200-250 aggro per proc.&nbsp; Thus, we gain less than warriors for using the proc (200-250 hate per proc vs 600-650 hate per proc for a warrior), and lose more (we lose a lifetap or manatap buff, warriors only lose a buff slot).&nbsp; Nice try, misguided all the same.<br><blockquote><i>"i&nbsp; have always&nbsp;understood the advantage of excess ability , it&nbsp; seems
that&nbsp;those oh&nbsp; so&nbsp; experienced&nbsp;knights in general&nbsp; who&nbsp; post&nbsp; on this
topic&nbsp; need to&nbsp; learn&nbsp; about&nbsp; their own&nbsp; excess aggro&nbsp; abilities and
how to&nbsp; use only&nbsp; enough&nbsp; to get the job&nbsp; done ."<br></i></blockquote>Try playing an SK before you make uninformed statements.&nbsp; Our aggro is certainly good- however, considering that SK's for most of EQ have been the highest aggro tank class in the game, it's no where near where it should be (a high end warrior isn't that far behind us in initial aggro, especially if they use recently available hate clickies to open a fight, and is at least as good in sustained aggro).&nbsp; When I'm plow tanking on a raid, I certainly don't have this massive excess aggro you're imagining.<br><br><hr size="2" width="100%"><br>Battleblade,<br><blockquote><i>"So sword and board is a downward scaling tool (or will be when we get
Shieldmate weapons) because it actually gets better in lesser content
where I'm not cutting down my DPS by using Defensive."</i><br></blockquote>You're doing a pretty good job building that "legacy" with totally uninformed comments like this one... we've already spelled out to you what a downward scaling ability is, and you still just don't get it.<br><div></div><p>Message Edited by josahd on <span class=date_text>03-13-2006</span> <span class=time_text>04:25 PM</span>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=175692" target=new>Josahd, Scourge Knight</a>
							</div>
								
